				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: HoH Pet<a name="51683"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 13 04 2:31 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I gave it a try last night, and man, was it worth it.
<br />

<br />
HoH has a unique agro environment.  If you agro a mob (well, maybe only those DC mobs), invis, and stay away from it, you can bring it pretty much anywhere w/o agroing other mobs on the way.  I brought one of those DC pets to RB.  Mobs went down considerably faster, and I was still doing pretty much what I've been doing - selos and mana songing the druid while twisting a few dots.  At 60 w/ a blood stained flute, I had practically no resists on either charm or mezz.  I rarely had to recharm during a fight (w/ 175 cha), and when I did, the few hits I -may- recieve were less than 5% damage, which my mana song fixed up quite fast (w/ my painted primal mask, no hardcore string swapping).  
<br />

<br />
We even decided to take on one of the named mobs in the basement, since we had a 62 war kiting around with us.  Both me and the druids used our pets as additional damage and the mob went down pretty fast.
<br />

<br />
Two things I figured out were:
<br />
1) AFKs must be short, obviously.  Mezz your pet away from the group, have the druid root it.  Depending on whether your mezz pushes or pulls, set yourself up so that it is just on the edge of your mez radius and will move through you.  You can get a few min that way.
<br />

<br />
2) At some point, the headache of dealing w/ a non DC pet will have diminishing returns, depending on the dps of the kite group.  Adding 1 pet is very significant, adding a 2nd is less so.  Adding a 6th, for instance, may very well be negligible.  Then again, by that point, so are our dots, so we're just mana batteries by that point.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
